Got some turns in today for the late, great Warren Miller. Had to take it easy, as it was the first time skiing after a back injury, but it felt good to honor the legend. 
For those of you who don‚Äôt know, Warren Miller was the pioneer, OG, and creator of ski movies (and action sports movies in general). I couldn‚Äôt even begin to count how many times I‚Äôve watched his 1997 film, Snowriders 2, or his 1998 film, Freeriders. His movies have been a part of my life since day one. Some of my earliest memories are sitting on the couch watching these movies with my dad and the running around the living room jumping off couches, pretending we were skiing (before actually skiing the next day, of course), and singing the songs from the movies. They are some of the first movies, and first songs I ever remember seeing/ hearing. It was a long-time dream of mine as a kid to be a pro skier and star in his movies. While I‚Äôve come to terms that God has not called me to the pro-skier route, Warren‚Äôs influence remains huge in my life. He always emphasized how skiing brought freedom. Pure freedom. It was something I never understood as a kid watching his movies, but as I‚Äôve gotten older, I understand it now. Skiing is a fantasy world. A much needed escape from the crap of this world. A place where you never have to grow up. And Warren preached that. He always said, ‚ÄúIf you don‚Äôt do it this year, you‚Äôll be one year older when you do,‚Äù and three years ago I embraced that and decided to give up running at a collegiate level and chose to ski instead; first in Wyoming and now Bozeman. This is a decision I haven‚Äôt regretted once. Thank you Warren for all you‚Äôve done for the sport, and for instilling a deep love of skiing in me. Your legacy will live on in the hearts of skiers everywhere. .

Living in Montana, I‚Äôm alway in awe of the skiers that learned on these mountains. I remember going down the ski hill (an actual landfill) in southern Wisconsin and being nervous. The skiers here rip shoots and cliffs like they came out of the womb clipped into a pair of powder skis. It‚Äôs been several years for me now, living in the Rocky Mountains and learning from the best. But skiing at @bridgerbowl keeps me humble. Both of these shots were taken at #saberslice and both of these guys killed it. The second guy sent it with two different skis on. After witnessing that, I can never complain about my setup again. .
